{"title_page": "S. P. B. Mais", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n'''Stuart Petre Brodie Mais''' (4 July 1885 \u2013 21 April 1975), known publicly as '''S. P. B. Mais''', was a British author, journalist and broadcaster. He was an author of travel books and guides, and had an informal style that made him popular with the general public.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |title=Mr. S. P. B. Mais |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=The Times Digital Archive |page= 18|date=24 April 1975 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nPetre Mais, as he was known in his personal life,<ref name=\"Nicholas Shakespeare 2002, p. 208\">\"SPB Mais\", Nicholas Shakespeare, in The Best Australian Essays 2002, ed. Peter Craven, Black Inc., 2002, p. 208</ref> was the son of Rev. John Brodie Stuart Mais, curate of [[St Margaret's Church, Ladywood|St Margaret's]], [[Ladywood]], [[Birmingham]] and his wife Hannah Horden (n\u00e9e Tamlin). He was born at Ladywood, but raised in [[Tansley]], Derbyshire, where his family relocated on his father's appointment as rector there in 1890.<ref>https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-46344</ref><ref name=\"Who 1932, p. 267\">Who's Who Among Living Authors of Older Nations, vol. I 1931-1932, ed. A. Lawrence, Golden Syndicate Publishing Company, 1932, p. 267</ref><ref>Crockford's Clerical Directory, fifty-ninth issue, Oxford University Press, 1930, p. 845</ref>\n\nHe was educated at [[Denstone College]], Staffordshire, then read English Literature at [[Christ Church, Oxford]] (BA 1909, [[Master of Arts (Oxford, Cambridge, and Dublin)|MA]] 1913) <ref name=\"Who 1932, p. 267\"/> After teaching at [[Rossall School|Rossall]], [[Sherborne School|Sherborne and Tonbridge]], and [[Royal Air Force College Cranwell]], he later worked for [[National Press]] at Fleet Street.<ref name=\"times\"/> A prolific author of over 200 books, he also broadcast for numerous wireless programmes for the [[BBC]] between the 1920s and 1940s. Mais was an ardent campaigner for the English countryside and traditions, leading walks for people who came for a day trip by train from big cities, often from London.\n\nMais worked as a journalist for ''[[The Oxford Times]]'' newspaper, and also for the BBC as a radio broadcaster, most famously on the ''Kitchen Front'' radio show that aired after the morning news during World War Two.<ref>For an account of these broadcasts see ''Calling Again \u2013 My Kitchen Front Talks with some results on the listener'' by S. P. B. Mais, 1941.</ref> He presented ''Letter from America'' from 1933, 13 years before a similar concept was made famous by [[Alistair Cooke]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} He also presented a series on ''This Unknown Island''.\n\nOne grandson is ''[[Evening Standard]]'' writer Sebastian Shakespeare, who wrote of his grandfather:\n{{quote|My grandfather, S. P. B. Mais, wrote more than 200 books and was a household name in his day. Prolific production alas was no guarantee of riches. He wrote to keep the bailiffs at bay. I'll never forget when my mother told me how she once had to hand over the contents of her piggy bank to his creditors.<ref>Sebastian Shakespeare, [http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23657322-details/Being+a+writer+is+a+poor+choice+of+job/article.do Being a writer is a poor choice of job], ''London Evening Standard''. Retrieved 22 September 2014.</ref>}}\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1913, Mais married Doris Snow; they had two daughters: Priscilla (1916\u20131982) and Vivien (born 1920).<ref>The Collected Letters of Robinson Jeffers, with selected letters of Una Jeffers, volume two, 1931-1939, ed. James Karman, Stanford University Press, 2011, pp. 273, 280-1, 301</ref> After the marriage was dissolved (they never divorced), he had a relationship with Winifred Doughty (1905\u20131993), who changed her name by deed poll to Gillian (\"Jill\") Mais; they also had two daughters.<ref>The Collected Letters of Robinson Jeffers, with selected letters of Una Jeffers, volume two, 1931-1939, ed. James Karman, Stanford University Press, 2011, p. 274</ref> After becoming dissatisfied with living standards in the tiny retirement home at [[Lindfield, Sussex]] that had been offered to the penniless Mais by the Samaritan Housing Association, along with Mais's refusal to marry her, Jill left Mais for a mutual friend, Dudley Carew, whom she married, and lived with him across the road from Mais, taking him meals.<ref>\"SPB Mais\", Nicholas Shakespeare, in The Best Australian Essays 2002, ed. Peter Craven, Black Inc., 2002, pp. 207-208</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMais died on 21 April 1975 at his retirement accommodation [[Lindfield, Sussex]].<ref name=\"Nicholas Shakespeare 2002, p. 208\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Critical works===\n* ''Delight in Books'' (1931)\n* ''A Chronicle of English Literature'' (1936)\n\n===Novels===\n* ''The Education of a Philanderer'' (1919)\n* ''Prunello'' (1924)\n* ''Eclipse'' (1925)\n* ''Perissa'' (1925)\n* ''Orange Street'' (1926)\n* ''Light over Lundy'' (1938)\n\n===Travel books===\nThese include:\n* ''See England First'' (1927)\n* ''Do you know North Cornwall? My finest holiday'' (1927 for the Southern Railway)\n* ''The [[Cornish Riviera Express#Publicity|Cornish Riviera]]'' (1928 for the [[Great Western Railway]])\n* ''Glorious Devon'' (1928 for the Great Western Railway)\n* ''North Wales'' (1928 for the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]])\n* ''Sussex'' 1929\n* ''It isn't far from London'' (1930)\n* ''Southern rambles for Londoners'' (1931 for the [[Southern Railway (Great Britain)|Southern Railway]])\n* ''The Highlands of Britain'' (1932)\n* ''This unknown island'' (1932)\n* ''Week-ends in England'' (1933)\n* ''Isles of the island'' (1934)\n* ''England's pleasance'' (1935)\n* ''Lovely Britain edited'' (1935)\n* ''Round about England'' (1935)\n* ''Southern schools'' (1935 for the Southern Railway)\n* ''Pictorial Britain and Ireland'' (ca1936 for the Anglo-American Oil Co \u2013 [[Esso]])\n* ''England's Character'' (1936)\n* ''A.C.E: the [[Atlantic Coast Express]]'' (1937 for the Southern Railway)\n* ''Britain calling'' (1938)\n* ''Let's get out here'' (1938 for the Southern Railway)\n* ''Walking in Somerset'' (1938)\n* ''Highways and Byways in the Welsh Marches'' (1939)\n* ''Hills of the South'' (1939)\n* ''I Return to Scotland'' (1947)\n* ''I Return to Switzerland'' (1948)\n* ''I Return to Ireland'' (1948)\n* ''I Return to Wales'' (1949)\n* ''Little England Beyond Wales'' (1949)\n* ''The Land of The Cinque Ports'' (illus. by [[Rowland Hilder]]) (1949)\n* ''The Riviera \u2013 New Look and Old'' (1950)\n* ''We Wander in the West'' (1950)\n* ''Arden and Avon'' (1951)\n* ''Norwegian Odyssey'' (1951)\n* ''The Channel Islands'' (1953)\n* ''Our Village Today'' (1956)\n* ''Majorcan Holiday'' (with Gillian Mais) (1956)\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Mais |first=S. P. B. |title=All the Days of My Life |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.174202 |location=London |publisher=Hutchinson |year=1937 }} (autobiography) \n* {{cite book |last=Mais |first=S. P. B. |title=The Happiest Days of My Life |location=London |publisher=Max Parrish |year=1953 }} (autobiography) \n* {{cite book |last=Robson |first=Maisie |title=An Unrepentant Englishman: The Life of S. P. B. Mais, Ambassador of the Countryside |location=Huddersfield |publisher=King's England Press |year=2005 |url=http://www.kingsengland.com/an-unrepentant-englishman-c2x8930497 }}\n*  {{cite book |first=Nicholas |last=Shakespeare |authorlink=Nicholas Shakespeare |title=Priscilla: The Hidden Life of an Englishwoman in Wartime France |location=London |publisher=Harvill Secker |year=2013 |isbn=9781846554834 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/priscillahiddenl0000shak }}  There are many references to Mais in this book about his daughter, the author's aunt.\n* {{ODNBweb |first=Bernard |last=Smith |title=Mais, Stuart Petre Brodie (1885\u20131975) |origyear=2004 |year=2014 |edition=online |id=46344 }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.walkmag.co.uk/blogs/eugene-suggett-an-80th-anniversary/ Eugene Suggett: An 80th anniversary]\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Mais,+S.+P.+B. | name=S. P. B. Mais}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Stuart Petre Brodie Mais}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mais, Petre}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:English travel writers]]\n[[Category:English broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:People from Derbyshire Dales (district)]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People from Ladywood]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n'''Stuart Petre Brodie Mais''' (4 July 1885 \u2013 21 April 1975), known publicly as '''S. P. B. Mais''', was a British author, journalist and broadcaster. He was an author of travel books and guides, and had an informal style that made him popular with the general public.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |title=Mr. S. P. B. Mais |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=The Times Digital Archive |page= 18|date=24 April 1975 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nPetre Mais, as he was known in his personal life,<ref>\"SPB Mais\", Nicholas Shakespeare, in The Best Australian Essays 2002, ed. Peter Craven, Black Inc., 2002, p. 208</ref> was the son of Rev. John Brodie Stuart Mais, curate of [[St Margaret's Church, Ladywood|St Margaret's]], [[Ladywood]], [[Birmingham]] and his wife Hannah Horden (n\u00e9e Tamlin). He was born at Ladywood, but raised in [[Tansley]], Derbyshire, where his family relocated on his father's appointment as rector there in 1890.<ref>https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-46344</ref><ref>Who's Who Among Living Authors of Older Nations, vol. I 1931-1932, ed. A. Lawr